mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub></math> basic character <math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>pK</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>&#60;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29840,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Let the mass of organic compound = m g</p><p>Volume of nitrogen collected = V<sub>1 </sub>mL</p><p>Room temperature = T<sub>1</sub>K</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn><mi>ml</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>280</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mi>total</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub></math>= Atmospheric pressure &ndash; Aqueous tension</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>759</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mi>mmHg</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>22400</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>.</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mL</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>gas</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>at</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>STP</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>weighs</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></mrow><mn>22400</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi>z</mi></msub></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>744</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>78</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>760</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>082</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>280</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>00097</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mi>Nitrogen</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></math>g</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02716</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>125</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>728</mn></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29678,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["3-Bromo-2-hydroxy-5-nitrobenzoic acid","3-Bromo-4-hydroxy-1-nitrobenzoic acid","2-Hydroxy-3-bromo-5-nitrobenzoic acid","5-Nitro-3-bromo-2-hydroxybenzoic acid"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_Nion4jDxxaifI8CMq3cwg_AxtPQlKmiH-kqdhAFzBc.original.fullsize.png\"/><br />IUPAC 3-Bromo-2-hydroxy-5-nitro-Benzoic acid","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29887,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><munder><msubsup><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mrow><mi>vf</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><munder><mrow><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>&#10230;</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>vf</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><msup><mi>Mn</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Mili equ. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>MnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mmultiscripts><mo>=</mo><mprescripts/><none/><mo>-</mo></mmultiscripts></math>&nbsp;mili equ. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>]</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>[</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>]</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>5</mn></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mfrac><mtext>&#160;mole&#160;</mtext><mtext>&#160;Lit&#160;</mtext></mfrac></math></p><p>Strength of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>158</mn><mfrac><mi>gram</mi><mi>Lit</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>316</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29818,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Sulphanilic acid is p-amino benzene sulphonic acid. It&nbsp;has no &ndash;COOH group hence no esterification test for carboxyl group.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/087939aa-ed4c-46df-85ae-1a3ece4c1010-9896856.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 172px;\" /></p><p>But it has sulphur, and nitrogen atom hence gives red colour in Lassigne&#39;s test for extra element detection.</p><p>Hence, statement I is incorrect but statement II is correct.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29809,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C, A, D, B","C, A, B, D&nbsp;","A, C, D, B","A, C, B, D"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The stability of a carbocation increases with the number of alkyl groups attached to the carbon atom, due to the inductive and hyperconjugation effects of the alkyl groups. The more the number of alkyl groups, the greater is the electron density on the positively charged carbon, and hence the more stable is the carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/15fcb8ee-2e3d-4869-b617-f1da716fe54c.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 104px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>The above carbocation can be stabilised by resonance and hyperconjugation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7878c7e7-d4f9-4ea6-b738-d566fcb47f73.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 102px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation stabilised by resonance caused by three benzene rings. This carbocation is more stable than the previous carbocation.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b7c796bc-90a4-44df-82e3-dfba0897a3cb.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 110px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation stabilised by hyperconjugation. It is the least stable carbocation among the four carbocations given.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f08e1a51-1ec1-49a4-bfbb-17b2223fdac1.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 131px;\" /></p><p>The above carbocation is the most stable carbocation among the four due to the resonance caused by bent orbitals.</p><p>From the given options Stability of carbocation:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p><p>The least stable carbocation will have the highest hydride affinity, because it is the most electron deficient and has the highest positive charge density. As a result, it will have the strongest attraction for a negatively charged hydride ion.</p><p>Hydride affinity order:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29810,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["C &gt; E &gt; D &gt; B &gt; A","E &gt; D &gt; C &gt; B &gt; A","D &gt; E &gt; C &gt; A &gt; B","E &gt; C &gt; D &gt; A &gt; B"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The compounds A &amp; B are alcohols, and rest of the compounds are phenols. Phenols are more acidic than alcohols. Among the A &amp;B, methyl alcohol is more acidic than tertiary butyl alcohol as alkyl groups decreases the acidic nature by electron releasing tendency. Among the phenols, the phenol with electron withdrawing group is more acidic.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>(Electron withdrawing group) group will increase the acidity, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>(Electron releasing&nbsp;group) group at para position will decrease the acidity.</p><p>So, Acidic strength&nbsp;E&gt;C&gt;D&gt;A&gt;B</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29828,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>HCl</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Lassaigne&#39;s test gives presence of chlorine and nitrogen in organic compound by fusion of organic compound in the presence of sodium. The fused products in this case are:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>.</mo><mi>HCl</mi><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>fusion</mi><mi>Na</mi></munderover><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NaCl</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCN</mi></math> gives +ve test for nitrogen and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi></math> gives +ve test for halogen.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29727,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Four","Two","One","Three"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Q060Y9NTtOvog1E0NH7WmY4XsecTN5BrWrtCuaSMUNM.original.fullsize.png\"><br />only one $2^{\\circ}$ carbon is present in this compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29969,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding and resonance stabilization, enol content is maximum in&nbsp;<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math>.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/486fd3a3-7536-4a03-a497-4cb7b0810240-image.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 178px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29913,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>For detection of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;the following test is used. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COOH</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>HNO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msup><mi>COO</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dc6e92b8-9149-4443-a711-e5783e70707a-image.png\" style=\"width: 386px; height: 487px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29984,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["II moves slower and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I","II moves faster and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I","I moves faster and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than II","I moves slower and has higher $\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value than I"],"answer":1,"solution":"Since, adsorption of I $>$ II, I is firmly attached to column (stationary phase). Hence, it will move slowly and will move little distance. A1so II is loosely attached to column (stationary phase). Hence, it will move faster and will move large distance.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":29651,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["B & D only","A, C & D only","B, D & E only","A, D & E only"],"answer":0,"solution":"Evaluating each statement:<br><b>(A)</b> TRUE - More covalent bonds with lesser charge separation increases resonance stabilization.<br><b>(B)</b> FALSE - In electromeric effect, unsaturated systems show +E effect toward nucleophiles and -E effect toward electrophiles, opposite to stated.<br><b>(C)</b> TRUE - Inductive effect of polar groups affects melting points, boiling points, and dipole moments.<br><b>(D)</b> FALSE - Greater alkyl substitution on doubly bonded carbons decreases heat of hydrogenation (more substituted alkenes are more stable).<br><b>(E)</b> TRUE - Higher s-character of orbital holding negative charge increases carbanion stability.<br><br>Statements NOT true: B and D. Therefore answer is B & D only.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30075,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{NaOH}$","ammonical $\\mathrm{AgNO}_3$","$\\mathrm{Na}$","$\\mathrm{HCl}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8JNCoX4CEo8aPVtwPZksLbtc83g9cafoVBXzcblVoJs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":29664,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":3,"solution":"Statement I:<br><br>Two chiral centre and due to presence of $-COOH$ compound dissolves in $NaHCO_3$.<br>Statement II:<br><br>Two $sp^3$ carbons, one $sp^2$ carbon, and one $sp$ carbon.<br>Both statements are true.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":29716,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["\\((\\mathrm{B})  < (\\mathrm{D}) < (\\mathrm{C}) < (\\mathrm{A}) < (\\mathrm{E})\\)","\\(\\text { (D) }  < \\text { (E) } < \\text { (C) } < \\text { (B) } < \\text { (A) }\\)","\\(\\text { (E) }  < \\text { (D) } < (\\text { C }) < (\\text { B }) < (\\text { A })\\)","\\(\\text { (E) }  < \\text { (D) } < \\text { (B) } < \\text { (A) } < \\text { (C) }\\)"],"answer":0,"solution":"Acidic strength order :-\n$\\mathrm{B}>\\mathrm{D}>\\mathrm{C}>\\mathrm{A}>\\mathrm{E}$\nCorrect $\\mathrm{pKa}$ Order :\n$\\text { B } < \\text { D } < \\text { C } < \\text { A } < \\text { E }$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":29845,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Organic Chemistry","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>36</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>03</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>38</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The Carius halogen method in analytical chemistry is a method for the quantitative determination of halogens in chemical substances. A known mass of an organic compound is heated with fuming nitric acid in the presence of silver nitrate contained in a hard glass tube known as Carius tube, in a furnace.</p><p>Mass of organic compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p>Mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math> obtained&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>Moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn></mrow><mn>188</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> Mass of Bromine&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>36</mn></mrow><mn>188</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>80</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1532</mn><mi>gm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>%</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;in compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1532</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>04</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null}]